description:
Introducing the Youth Farm Box at the Berkeley Farmers' Market! 
Order your farm-fresh produce box for contactless pickup
ORDER LINK: https://ecology-center-youth-farm-box.square.site/
farmbox@ecologycenter.org 
(510) 697-4808

Produce boxes are now available for preorder and curbside pickup weekly at the Downtown Berkeley Farmers' Market. Boxes will have a variety of local, seasonal fruit, vegetables, and salad greens from market vendors. Purchases support farmers in our local food system as well as employment opportunities for youth in our community.

How it Works
•	Select your pick up window, order and pay online through our secure Square site by Thursday 9:00 AM.
•	On Saturday morning, our Youth Environmental Academy staff will gather fruits and veggies from farmers and pack your box.
•	Pick it up at the farmers market during your confirmed pick-up window curbside at 1980 Allston Way (pull in from Milvia St).
•	Give a team member your name and/or order number. Pop your trunk and we'll load your box!

We accept CalFresh/EBT
To order using CalFresh/EBT, please give us a call at (510) 697-4808.

The Youth Farm Box is a pilot project of the Ecology Center's Youth Environmental Academy in partnership with the Berkeley Farmers' Markets and is supported with funding from the City of Berkeley, Healthy Berkeley program.
title: Introducing the Youth Farm Box at the Berkeley Farmers' Market!

description:
Performing Arts - Music | January 14 | 7 p.m. |  Online
Speakers/Performers:  Julia Bullock; Laura Poe
Sponsor:  Cal Performances
Cal Performances audiences know the superb, daring soprano Julia Bullock well, from her 2018 Hertz Hall recital, and before that, in her star turns as both Josephine Baker and French mystic and activist Simone Weil at the 2016 Ojai at Berkeley festival. Just before this springs lockdown, Bullock visited the Bay Area to sing with the San Francisco Symphony, where the San Francisco Chronicle praised the dramatic power and clarity of her interpretations, and her ability to plunge unnervingly deep into this music and then surface, like some kind of musical pearl diver, with great glistening strands of expressive jewels. Recording this recital from her home city of Munich, Bullock presents one of her characteristically diverse and thoughtfully curated programs, traversing art song, contemporary works, and selections from African-American jazz and blues.

Following the premiere, this performance will be available to view on demand for three months until April 14, 2021.
Target audience:  All Audiences
Open to audience:  All Audiences
Tickets required: $15 for a single viewer, $30 for two viewers, and $60 per household viewing. $5 tickets are available for UC Berkeley students.
Ticket info:   Buy tickets online or by calling 510-642-9988, or by emailing tickets@calperformances.org
Event contact:  510-642-9988
Access Coordinator:  Marybeth Baluyot,  mbaluyot@calperformances.org,  510-642-9988

description:
Introducing the Youth Farm Box at the Berkeley Farmers' Market! 
Order your farm-fresh produce box for contactless pickup
ORDER LINK: https://ecology-center-youth-farm-box.square.site/
farmbox@ecologycenter.org 
(510) 697-4808

Produce boxes are now available for preorder and curbside pickup weekly at the Downtown Berkeley Farmers' Market. Boxes will have a variety of local, seasonal fruit, vegetables, and salad greens from market vendors. Purchases support farmers in our local food system as well as employment opportunities for youth in our community.

How it Works
•	Select your pick up window, order and pay online through our secure Square site by Thursday 9:00 AM.
•	On Saturday morning, our Youth Environmental Academy staff will gather fruits and veggies from farmers and pack your box.
•	Pick it up at the farmers market during your confirmed pick-up window curbside at 1980 Allston Way (pull in from Milvia St).
•	Give a team member your name and/or order number. Pop your trunk and we'll load your box!

We accept CalFresh/EBT
To order using CalFresh/EBT, please give us a call at (510) 697-4808.

The Youth Farm Box is a pilot project of the Ecology Center's Youth Environmental Academy in partnership with the Berkeley Farmers' Markets and is supported with funding from the City of Berkeley, Healthy Berkeley program.

People regularly gather in the area where the shooting occurred on other days, particularly weekends.

This is the detail for a severe weather event that has occurred. The original alert for this event is listed below. 

Details of the original alert: 

 

 -  WHAT: Forecast highs from the 90s to 105 F in the interior North Bay and East Bay. Overnight lows will be in the 60s and 70s in the hills, so expect little overnight relief. These will be some of our hottest temperatures of the year thus far. 


 -  WHERE: North Bay Mountains, North Bay Interior Valleys, East Bay Interior Valleys and East Bay Hills and the Diablo Range. 


 -  WHEN: Until 9 PM PDT Monday.



 -  IMPACTS: Increased risk of heat related illnesses such as heat exhaustion and heat stroke can occur due to prolonged exposure to hot temperatures. People most vulnerable include those who spend extended periods outdoors, those without air conditioning, young children, the elderly, and those with chronic illness.



 -  ADDITIONAL DETAILS: Those seeking relief at area beaches should be mindful of cold water temperatures and dangerous rip currents.

description: Mark Morris Dance Group and Philharmonia Baroque join forces once again in a revival of Jean-Philippe Rameau’s masterpiece Platée, the story of a homely yet vain nymph who falls prey to a prank set by the gods. This production, with costumes by Isaac Mizrahi, premiered at Zellerbach Hall in 1998. Platée was among the most highly regarded of Rameau’s operas during his lifetime, and it was even well received by the royal family who commissioned it—for the nuptials of the son of King Louis XV of France and Maria Theresa of Spain. In an act of comic genius, Rameau created the role of Platée to be sung by a (male) high tenor, here played by the French tenor Mathias Vidal. Morris’ choreography mixes high camp with supreme craft, the movement always sensitive to the richness of the effervescent Baroque score. Sung in French with English supertitles.
title: Mark Morris Dance Group and Philharmonia Baroque Orchestra & Chorale; Platée

description: NOTE ABOUT THE REIGSTRATION PROCESS:  As we wait for our permit to be issued, we will use a pre-registration option for sign-ups.  You will not be charged for the registration until we are confirmed that the race will happen. During the process, you fill in all of your registration details including your credit card information. We perform a $0 credit card authorization charge to validate the card and then securely save the card information. You will not be charged for the registration until selected and will be shown as a pending pre-registration selection. Once we have our permit from the city if Alameda, we will charge the saved credit cards and update the registration statuses to active.Get all of the Bay Area views in a flat and fast 10 miler. Our goal is to provide a safe, fun, and unique event along the water in beautiful Alameda. The 10 mile course follows the Bay Trail path along the water, cruising through Crab cove and with a turn around just south of Crown Beach Memorial. Love boats? Love the beach? Love local hops? Come run Alameda with us!Brought you by the team at the Oakland Marathon and Corrigan Sports

description:
This is the detail for a severe weather event that has occurred. The original alert for this event is listed below. 

Details of the original alert: 

 

 -  WHAT: Minor coastal flooding expected at prone low lying coastal locations across the San Francisco Bay shoreline during peak high tide through Monday.



 -  WHERE: Low lying portions of the San Francisco Bayshore. Localized impacts are also possible in low lying areas along the Pacific shore as well, such as near Elkhorn Slough. 


 -  WHEN: From 9 AM to 3 PM PST Tuesday.



 -  IMPACTS: Flooding of areas previously impacted by King Tide events is expected, including low lying lots, parks, and roads throughout the San Francisco Bay Shoreline with the highest high tides.



 -  ADDITIONAL DETAILS: Tidal levels are forecast to subside but rising seas due to building swell and storm surge will offset the differences during high tide on Tuesday. Thus, localized flooding of low lying coastal locations is possible again Tuesday from 9AM to 3PM. Check local tide forecasts for high tide times as these can vary and occur anywhere between mid morning to early afternoon.

This is the detail for a severe weather event that has occurred. The original alert for this event is listed below. 

Details of the original alert: 

 

 -  WHAT: Urban and small stream flooding caused by excessive rainfall is expected.



 -  WHERE: A portion of northern California, including the following counties, Alameda, Contra Costa, Marin, Napa, San Francisco, San Mateo and Sonoma.



 -  WHEN: Until 1015 AM PST.



 -  IMPACTS: Minor flooding in low-lying and poor drainage areas. Ponding of water in urban or other areas is occurring or is imminent.



 -  ADDITIONAL DETAILS.

- At 810 AM PST, Doppler radar indicated heavy rain over the greater San Francisco Bay Area. This will cause urban and small stream flooding, especially in low-lying and poor drainage areas where culverts may be blocked.

- Some locations that will experience flooding include. San Francisco, Oakland, Berkeley, Richmond, Daly City, Napa, Alameda, San Rafael, Novato, Martinez, San Pablo, Lafayette, El Cerrito, Hercules, American Canyon, Albany, Pinole,

Orinda, Mill Valley and San Anselmo.

 -  WHAT: Urban and small stream flooding caused by excessive rainfall is expected along an approaching frontal boundary.

 -  WHEN: Until 100 AM PST.



 -  IMPACTS: Minor flooding in low-lying and poor drainage areas. Water over roadways. Overflowing poor drainage areas. Ponding of water in urban or other areas is occurring or is imminent.

- At 1043 PM PST, Doppler radar indicated heavy rain producing one-quarter to one-half inch of rainfall per hour. This will cause urban and small stream flooding. Overflowing poor drainage areas will cause minor flooding in the advisory area.

- Some locations that will experience flooding include. San Francisco, Oakland, Concord, Berkeley, Richmond, Daly City, San Leandro, Mountain View, Alameda, Walnut Creek, South San Francisco, San Bruno, Pacifica, Martinez, Pleasant Hill, San Pablo, Lafayette, El Cerrito, San Lorenzo and Castro Valley.

description:
This is the detail for a severe weather event that has occurred. The original alert for this event is listed below. 

Details of the original alert: 

 

 -  WHAT: Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be possible.



 -  WHERE: A portion of northern California, including the following areas, East Bay Hills and the Diablo Range, East Bay Interior Valleys, San Francisco, San Francisco Bay Shoreline and Santa Clara Valley Including San Jose.



 -  WHEN: Until 10 PM PST this evening.



 -  IMPACTS: Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations. Creeks and streams may rise out of their banks. Flooding may occur in poor drainage and urban areas. Low-water crossings may be flooded. Storm drains and ditches may become clogged with debris. Extensive street flooding and flooding of creeks and rivers are possible.



 -  ADDITIONAL DETAILS.

- Periods of moderate to heavy rain will be possible through this evening.
